post_cb({"45359202": {"ParentId": "45358729", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>From that same section, emphasis mine:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_45358729_45359202_0\">In a linkage-specification, the specified language linkage applies to the function types of all function declarators, function names with <strong>external linkage</strong>, [...]</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>But, <code>f4</code> is declared <code>static</code>, which means that name has internal linkage per <a href=\"http://eel.is/c++draft/basic.link#3.1\" rel=\"noreferrer\">[basic.link]/3</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_45358729_45359202_1\">A name having namespace scope has internal linkage if it is the name of:  </p>\n<ul>\n<li>a variable, function or function template that is explicitly declared <code>static</code>; or, [...]</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hence, the C linkage doesn't apply. </p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "2069064", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "45359202", "Score": "5", "CreationDate": "2017-07-27T19:12:49.040", "LastActivityDate": "2017-07-27T19:12:49.040"}, "45358729": {"CommentCount": "2", "ViewCount": "76", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "5479741", "CreationDate": "2017-07-27T18:43:13.833", "LastActivityDate": "2017-07-27T19:12:49.040", "Title": "Why is it the case that the name of the function f4 has internal linkage, and not a C language linkage?", "AcceptedAnswerId": "45359202", "LastEditDate": "2017-07-27T18:44:27.687", "Id": "45358729", "Score": "5", "Body": "<p>The fifth example in <a href=\"http://eel.is/c++draft/dcl.link#4\" rel=\"noreferrer\">[dcl.link]/4</a> states the following:</p>\n<pre><code>extern \"C\" {\n    static void f4(); // the name of the function f4 has internal linkage (not C language linkage)\n                      // and the function\u2019s type has C language linkage.\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>Why is this? Why is it the case that the name of the function <code>f4</code> has internal linkage, and not a C language linkage?</p>\n<p>P.S.: I'm asking this from a perspective of a language-lawyer. That is, how can one derive the commented statement above, from normative paragraphs in the Standard?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><language-lawyer><linkage>", "OwnerUserId": "5479741", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_45358729_45359202_0": {"section_id": 5520, "quality": 1.0, "length": 14}, "so_45358729_45359202_1": {"section_id": 7136, "quality": 1.0, "length": 7}}, "n3337": {"so_45358729_45359202_0": {"section_id": 5306, "quality": 1.0, "length": 14}, "so_45358729_45359202_1": {"section_id": 6880, "quality": 1.0, "length": 7}}, "n4659": {"so_45358729_45359202_0": {"section_id": 6955, "quality": 1.0, "length": 14}, "so_45358729_45359202_1": {"section_id": 8637, "quality": 1.0, "length": 7}}}});